 ulve vegzik.Kepernyo elol el nem mozdulnanak,Napfenyt, fakat, mezot talan nem is latnak.Haziasszony nem foz, nincs helye panasznak,Wrigley's gumit ragnak, raja colat isznak.Zug a rock-pop "zene", artalmara fulnek,Honaprol-honapra egyre csak hulyulnek.Gyereket nevelni? Eszukbe sem szokik,Sokkal egyszerubb, ha TV ele lokik.Ott aztan fejlodnek, egyre okosodnak,Sokan nemhogy irni, olvasni sem tudnak.TV elott hasal egy kiszolgalt kutya,Evek ota nezi, azert olyan buta.Hazajon a gazda munkabol faradtanFolbont egy uveg sort, TV ele huppan.Uveges szemekkel bamulja a krimitEppen egy kispapnak szurjak ki a szemit.Autok nyikognak, robbannak a hazak,Kejelegve nezi, ahogy torkot vagnak.Emberevo capa kisgyermeket fal fel,Akit furdes kozben szuleitol mart el.Elvezi a csalad "Hasfelmetszo Jack"-et,S hogy kell bevaltani fedezetlen csekket.Bankot kirabolni csupan egy pillanat,Tisztviselot, rendort lovik mint a nyulat.Spriccel, folyik a ver, a padlo is sikos,Ilyenkor a TV-t kikapcsolni tilos.Fegyver nelkul jarni eletveszely ma'ma,Halaval gondolunk a "nagy" Amerikara.Hogy ez hova vezet, leirni is felek,Ettol "nemesedik" a gyermeki lelek.Pisztoly, bicska, bomba es egy rozsdas bo"ko",Igy ragyog elottunk egy uj es szebb jo"vo"...!===MAGYAROK VILAGSZOVETSEGE: FELHIVAS SZOLIDARITASI DEMONSTRACIORA        Egy szal gyertya az anyanyelvert        Ez ev julius 27-en a hataron tuli magyar nemzeti kozossegek anya-nyelv hasznalatat veszelyezteto tervek ellen nagygyulesen tiltakoztunk aDebreceni Nagytemplomban. Fajo, hogy azota felelmeink beteljesultek, aveszely erosodott, a harang hiaba szolt.        A roman parlament elfogadta az uj tanugyi torvenyt! A szlovakparlament az allamnyelv vedelmerol szolo torvenyt szavazott meg!Szerbiaban uj lendulettel tipor az etnikai uthenger. Romaniaban,Szlovakiaban a magyar anyanyelvueket minden eddiginel nagyobb csapas erte,soha nem tapasztalt modon korlatozzak az anyanyelv hasznalatat, hatalmikerdesse valt a magyar nyelv tiltasa.        Erosodik a cselekves kenyszere. Ezert szuksegesnek tartjuk, hogyismet folemeljuk szavunkat! A Magyarok Vilagszovetsege felhivassal fordulMagyarorszag, Erdely, Szlovakia, Karpatalja, Horvatorszag, Vajdasag,Szlovenia magyar kozossegeihez, s a vilag szorvanymagyarsagahoz.A humanusan gondolkodo kozvelemenyhez, hogy:        1996. januar 1-en, az esztendo elso napjanak estejen, helyi idoszerint 20 orakor minden egyutterzo ember egy szal gyertyat gyujtsonablakaban.        Apro kis tuzekkel - ahogyan a Szekelyfoldon tettek evszazadokoknat -,larmafakkal figyelmeztetunk a nemzeti kisebbsegek anyanyevet fenyegetoveszelyre. Kicsiny, de messzire latszo fenyekkel tiltakozunk a nyelvieroszak ellen!        A hataron tuli magyar nemzeti kozossegek anyanyelvhasznalatalegyen kozos gond. Egyutterzesunk, egyuttgondolkodasunk tegyen kozosseminden magyar ugyet.        Kerjuk a magyarsag hazai es hataron tuli szovetsegeseit, mozgalmait,partjait, hirkozlo szerveit, tarsuljanak felhivasunkhoz!        Legyen szolidaritas!        A Magyarok Vilagszovetsegenek Elnoksege(1995.  december 9. elnoksegi ules - Becs)===AZ EMIGRACIO EREJE - MAGYAR LOBBY(1) WWW "Home Page"-ekA "Nemzet" segitsegevel a magyarsag kiemelkedoen fontos feladatainakszolgalasara egy WWW ottlap letesult az alabbi URL-lel:http://www.siliconvalley.com/magyar.htmlErrol a laprol hyperlink-ek vezetnek egy"Hungarian Lobby - Magyar Lobby"  lapra:http://www.gabor.org/lobby.htmles a Kamatrabszolga-felszabaditas otthonlapjara:http://www.gabor.org/imf.htmlEzen WWW-lapokba szant anyagok anonymous ftp-vel felvihetok az alabbicimre:ftp.siliconvalley.com---(2) Liptak Bela akciosorazatanak ez evi zarokozlemenyeDear Colleagues,Our 3 month period of preparation is over. This is the last time that you cansign up to participate in the work of the Hungarian lobby by sending me anote to that effect. After the first of the year we will have a formal listof participants and you will be asked to subscribe directly to the HL-list.Unon subscribing, you will receive the "information letter" which is quotedbelow.Thanks to those of you who are responsible for the excellent article in theMiami Herald on the oppression of Hungarian national communities and thanksto all who helped to reach this pointHappy Holydays: Bela LiptakxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxWelcome to the Hungarian Lobby (HL) List,1996 will be the 1100th anniversary of Hungarian statehood, the 40thanniversary of the Hungarian Revolution. 1996 is also an election year in theUnited States, when the 1.58 million Hungarian-Americans could exercise (forthe first time ever) some political influence. HL's goal is protect Hungaryfrom defamation and to protect, not only the oppressed Hungarian nationalcommunities of the Danubian region, but all ethnic minorities, includingJews, Romas and others.The Hungarian Lobby (HL) is not a discussion group or a debating society. Ouroperation is action oriented, our goal is to influence our political leadersand the media thorugh the writing of letters and articles, which we send byE-mail, fax-broadcasting and regular mail. All HL participants are asked topost ALL  letters they send to their representatives or the press, so that weall can benefit from the ideas contained in them and can give support, if weagree with them. Similarly we would like you to post all news of law andhuman rights violations over-there, or of incomplete or erroneous reportingof Hungary-related news over-here. Please send E-mail letters or news itemsto:  hl@glue.umd.edu.If you want to take part in our fax-chainletter efforts, and IF you have anAUTOMATIC fax machine (one that accepts a fax message automatically: does notneed to be turned on manually ), please fax a note to Dr. Bollyky at203-967-4845.The home page of the Hungarian Lobby is at: http://mineral.umd.edu/hl/   It contains the E-Mail addresses and faxnumbers of all members of the USA Congress, Senate, Newspapers and othersoutside the USA.. Old letters and articles posted on HL can also be obtainedon the World Wide Web at the home page address:http://mineral.umd.edu/hl/archive/. A complete list of the addresses of ALLEuropean newspapers can be found at: http://www.dds.nl/~kidon/papers.htmlAccording to the present concept, the HL has no leaders. It is theassociation of people, who care about justice and human rights, who feel thattheir voice will be multiplied and their work will be more effective, if theyact together. Our present operation (which, I am sure will change with timeand experience), is as follows:  When a member (ANY MEMBER) of the HL feels,that we should speak up in connection with some deed or event, he or she willcompose a letter addressing that issue and send it to a political leader orto a newspaper AND IN ADDITION to the HL list. Members of HL, who agree withthe received text, will read the letter and if they agree with it, they toowill mail it (or some version of it) to their local papers and/or to theirpolitical representatives. In other words, all members of HL can initiate anaction or can participate in an action initiated by others,  if they agree.We have already succeeded to reach the point of sending several hundredletters within 24 hours of  learning about a human right abuse or an unlawfulact. Our goal is to increase that number into the thousands and to expand ourspan of attention to include such problem areas as environmental abuses, thedefense of open societies in general and the freedom of the press inparticular. In the following paragraphs, I will list the specific deeds thatwe ask of you, if you join the HL:1) HL members should keep the E-mail (or Fax) addresses of their President,Senators, Congressmen and local newspapers readily available for use, so whenthe occasion arises, they can send on a letter within minutes.2) We ask all HL members to agree that within 24 hours of receiving aform-letter, they will read it, and if they agree with its purpose, contentand style, they will send it (or some variety of it) on,  to their ownaddresses.3) We ask all HL members to agree, that when they initiate a chain-letter,they should carefully check the validity of its facts, should weigh theimportance of the topic and should use appropriate manners and style. Whenwriting to a Senator, you should be formal and brief. Two paragraphs are thebest, but should never exceed one page. You should identify yourself andoutline your concern in the first paragraph. In the second paragraph youshould outline why that concern is important to the United States. You shouldalways include your postal address in addition to your title and signature.(At the end of this letter, I am attaching a typical chain-letter as anexample.)4)  If you find the work of HL useful, please ask your friends and relativesto join us.With best personal regards:Bela LiptakLiptakbela@aol.comxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxTHE INDIVIDUALIZED FORM-LETTER:RE: Religious Discrimination In RomaniaPOTENTIAL ADDRESSES:President Bill Clinton: president@whitehouse.gov  fax: 202-456-2461VP Al Gore: vicepresident@whitehouse.gov  fax:202-973-2600Senator Robert Dole: fax: 202-228-1245Congressman Newton Gingrich: georgia6@hr.house.gov fax: 202-225-4656The Honorable ....Dear ....I am (A MEMBER, OFFICER, PRESIDENT ETC. OF XYZ ORGANIZATION, CHURCH,COMPANY...). Similarly to the 1.58 million American voters of Hungarianorigin, I too am concerned about the oppression of the indigenous Hungariannational community in Romania. I am particularly concerned about the newlanguage law which would destroy one of Europe's oldest, the Hungarian schoolsystem in Transylvania.I am also concerned that while the property of the Romanian Orthodox Church,which was also confiscated by the Communists, has been returned, the church property of the Hungarian national community, has still not been returned.It includes 1,041 schools, 28 boarding schools, 20 teachers residences, 16hospitals and orphanages, 126 priests' houses and 70 convents.Dear Mr. (PRESIDENT,  SENATOR, CONGRESSMAN...) It is in our national interestto be the moral and ethical leaders of the free world. Therefore, I  wouldlike to learn yourviews on this matter and the steps you might take to help alleviate thesuffering of the Hungarian national community in Romania. There is no morebasic human right as one's right to protect one's church, property and theright to speak one's mother tongue, enjoy  one's culture. In a country suchas Romania, which strives to enter the European Community, the civilizedworld should not allow these basic rights to be denied.I know, that a letter from you to President Iliescu of Romania would help tochange this situation. I would be honored if you decided to consider thisrecommendation of mine. I thank you in advance and assure you that I willwork very hard for your reelection.Respectfully yours,YOUR NAME, ADDRESS,TITLE===NEMZETKOZI KERDESEK - AZ OROSZ VALASZTAS ERTEKELESEOMRI SPECIAL REPORT: RUSSIAN ELECTION SURVEYNO. 15, 22 DECEMBER 1995Welcome to the last in OMRI's series of special reports on the RussianElection campaign. Distributed as a supplement to the OMRI Daily Digest,the Russian Election Survey was distributed twice a week until theelection in December with the latest news about developments in theelection campaign. Future supplements will also focus on importantevents in Eastern European countries.UPDATED SEAT ESTIMATES. With more than three-fourths of the party-listvotes counted and all 225 single-member seats determined, the 450 seatsin the new State Duma will be allocated among the top parties roughly asfollows:     % (party list)   party-list seats  single-member seats     total        (225 total)     (225 total)                        (projected)KPRF         22.0%          97                58                   155NDR           9.7%          42                10                    52Yabloko       7.1%          37                14                    51LDPR         11.2%          49                 1                    50APR           3.9%           0                20                    20DVR           4.0%           0                 9                     9VN             na            0                 9                     9KRO           4.3%           0                 5                     5ZhR           4.6%           0                 3                     3PST           4.0%           0                 1                     1KTR           4.6%           0                 0                     0Note: Independent candidates have won 77 out of the 225 single-memberseats, and a number of small parties have won up to three seats each.Abbreviations: Communist Party of the Russian Federation (KPRF), LiberalDemocratic Party of Russia (LDPR), Our Home Is Russia (NDR), Women ofRussia (ZhR), Agrarian Party of Russia (APR), Russia's Democratic Choice(DVR), Power to the People (VN), Congress of Russian Communities (KRO),Communists-Working Russia (KTR), Party of Workers' Self-Management(PST). (Source: ITAR-TASS on 22 December.) -- Laura BelinPARTIES AND POLITICIANSWELL-KNOWN POLITICIANS RETURN TO DUMA. Among the well-known incumbentsreturning for a second term in the Duma will be: Communist Party leaderGennadii Zyuganov, Liberal Democratic Party of Russia leader VladimirZhirinovsky, Yabloko leaders Grigorii Yavlinskii and Vladimir Lukin,former Supreme Soviet Speaker Anatolii Lukyanov, Duma Security CommitteeChairman Viktor Ilyukhin, Forward, Russia! leader Boris Fedorov, filmmaker Stanislav Govorukhin, Party of Russian Unity and Concord leaderSergei Shakhrai, Women of Russia leader Yekaterina Lakhova, Common Causeleader Irina Khakamada, television journalist Aleksandr Nevzorov, formerState Secretary Gennadii Burbulis, human rights activist Sergei Kovalev,current Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin, Duma Budget Committee Chairman MikhailZadornov, economist Pavel Bunich, businessman Artem Tarasov, DumaDefense Committee Chairman Sergei Yushenkov, cosmonaut German Titov,extreme nationalist Sergei Baburin, Duma Deputy Chairman ArturChilingarov, and Foreign Minister Andrei Kozyrev. At least four currentmembers of the Federation Council will join the Duma, Nikolai Gonchar,Ramazan Abdulatipov, Elena Mizulina, and Petr Romanov. -- Robert OrttungNEW FACES TO APPEAR IN DUMA. Well-known politicians joining the Duma forthe first time include: Party of Economic Freedom leader KonstantinBorovoi, Workers' Self-Management Party leader Svyatoslav Fedorov,former USSR Prime Minister Nikolai Ryzhkov, Lt. Gen. (ret.) AleksandrLebed, Col. Gen. Boris Gromov, cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, Col. Gen.(ret.) Albert Makashov, Democratic Russia leader Galina Starovoitova,former RSFSR Supreme Soviet First Deputy Chairman Yurii Voronin, formerRSFSR Supreme Soviet Deputy Chairwoman Svetlana Goryacheva, andcorruption investigator Telman Gdlyan. Mikhail Men, the son of slainpriest Aleksandr Men, will also be a member. Sergei Manyakin, a memberof the Communist Party of the Soviet Union Central Committee who in 1987launched a savage attack on Boris Yeltsin at a Central Committee meetingin which Yeltsin resigned from the Politburo, will join the Duma fromOmsk after campaigning with Power to the People. -- Robert OrttungMANY CELEBRITIES WILL NOT BE IN NEW DUMA. Although he ran third on theCommunist Party list, Aman Tuleev, chairman of the Kemerovo LegislativeAssembly, will not join the Duma because he wants to retain his post inthe local legislature. Our Home Is Russia leaders Prime Minister ViktorChernomyrdin, State Property Committee Chairman Sergei Belyaev, andGeneral Lev Rokhlin also will give up their seats to retain their oldjobs. Russia's Democratic Choice leader Yegor Gaidar, Congress ofRussian Communities leaders Yurii Skokov and Sergei Glazev, AgrarianParty leader Mikhail Lapshin cannot join the Duma since their partiesdid not clear the 5% barrier and they did not run in single-memberdistricts. Duma Press and Information Committee Chairman MikhailPoltoranin, hypnotist Anatolii Kashpirovskii, and former St. PetersburgLDPR leader Vyacheslav Marychev lost races and also will not rejoin theDuma. Aleksei Vedenkin, Russia's most famous "fascist," extremecommunist Viktor Anpilov, MMM President Sergei Mavrodi, former KGBGeneral Aleksandr Sterligov, and Bolshevik writer Eduard Limonov alsolost their races. -- Robert OrttungCHANGES IN STORE FOR MANY DUMA COMMITTEES. There will be changes at thetop of some of the most important Duma committees following therealignment of forces in parliament. The Communist Party will emergewith about three times as many seats as the second-largest party in theDuma, and will demand the lion's share of powerful committee posts. Bythe same token, Russia's Choice faction, formerly the largest inparliament, will have just nine members and will not retain any majorcommittees. Our Home Is Russia did not exist in the last parliament butwill have about 50 seats in the next one, and the pro-government blocwill certainly be given some committeesDuma Speaker. Although current Speaker Ivan Rybkin was elected from asingle-member district, he almost certainly will lose the speakership.The Communist Party (KPRF) wants the job, but according to the 20December Izvestiya, the smaller parties and independents will not allowa representative from a major faction to hold this post. If pastexperience is any guide, the search for a compromise figure will bedifficult and contentious. Rybkin was elected speaker by only one votein 1994Committee on Legislation. The current head of this committee, AgrarianVladimir Isakov, will no longer be in the Duma, since he did not contesta single-member seat and his party failed to win 5% of the vote. TheKPRF reportedly wants this post to go to Svetlana Goryacheva, who wassecond on their national party listCommittee on Labor and Social Security. The committee is currentlyheaded by LDPR member Sergei Kalashnikov, one of the few members ofZhirinovsky's party who frequently speaks in public about policy issues.At an 18 December press conference, Gennadii Zyuganov specifically namedKalashnikov as one of the LDPR members he can work with (although closecooperation between the Communist leader and Zhirinovsky himself is outof the question). Consequently, Kalashnikov may retain his postBudget Committee. Current Chairman Mikhail Zadornov, a Yabloko member,was re-elected in a single-member district and may keep the top post inthis committee, since Yabloko has increased its Duma representationDefense Committee. Current Chairman Sergei Yushenkov of Russia's Choicewas re-elected in a single-member district, but he is sure to lose thiscommittee now that his party will only have nine seats in parliament.Possible replacements include 1991 coup plotter and Communist ValentinVarennikov, 1993 coup leader Albert Makashov, Aleksandr Lebed, and BorisGromovCommittee on Economic Policy. Current Chairman Sergei Glazev split theDemocratic Party to become third on the party list for the Congress ofRussian Communities (KRO). Since KRO was believed to be a sure bet forclearing the 5% barrier, Glazev did not contest a single-member districtand will consequently not be in the new parliamentCommittee on Property and Privatization. Current head Sergei Burkov ofthe New Regional Policy faction contested a single-member district as amember of KRO and lost. The KPRF will certainly want this committee.Zyuganov has said that changing government policy on privatization willbe one of his top prioritiesCommittee on Agrarian Affairs. Although the Agrarian Party did not clearthe 5% barrier, it won 20 single-member seats and may therefore retainthe leadership of this committee. However, the 21 December Kommersant-Daily predicted that this committee would pass to the control of theKPRFPress and Information Committee. Current Chairman Mikhail Poltoraninwill not be a member of the next Duma. He was elected as a member ofRussia's Choice 1993, but left Yegor Gaidar's faction and ranunsuccessfully for parliament this year as an independentForeign Affairs Committee. Yabloko leader Viktor Lukin was re-elected onthe party list and is a favorite to keep his job at the head of thiscommittee. He has been mentioned as a possible replacement for ForeignMinister Andrei Kozyrev, who will probably leave his cabinet post toserve in the Duma. However, Lukin would be unlikely to accept such anofferSecurity Committee. Communist Viktor Ilyukhin is a strong contender toremain the head of the Security Committee, since the Communists havetripled their Duma representation. However, Ilyukhin's name has beenmentioned as a possible speakerCIS Affairs Committee. Current Chairman Konstantin Zatulin, who likeGlazev left the Democratic Party for KRO, will lose this post since hefailed to win a single-member seat in the DumaGeopolitics Committee. Currently headed by Viktor Ustinov, thiscommittee may cease to exist in the new Duma, according to the 21December Kommersant-Daily. Zhirinovsky, among others, has lobbied forits abolition since Ustinov, who was elected on the LDPR party list in1993, deserted the party for the Stability faction in early 1995.Ustinov ran for a single-member seat for the Bloc of Ivan Rybkin butlost. -- Laura BelinRUSSIANS ABROAD ALSO TURN OUT TO VOTE. At a 19 December news conference,Foreign Ministry spokesperson Valentina Matvienko told journalists thatRussians living outside the CIS had turned out to vote this year ingreater numbers than in 1993, ITAR-TASS reported. Matvienko said that390 polling stations had been set up in 145 countries. Of the about180,000 Russian citizens eligible to vote who reside outside the CIS,42,763 cast ballots. Among those Russians, Yabloko won the most votes,followed by Our Home Is Russia, the Communist Party (KPRF), Russia'sDemocratic Choice, and the Congress of Russian Communities (KRO). Adifferent picture emerged among Russian citizens who reside in thecountries of the "near abroad," including the CIS and the Baltic states.Of the approximately 200,000 Russian voters there, about 64,000 voted,with the KPRF taking the largest share of the vote, followed by KRO,NDR, and the Agrarian Party. Since an estimated 25 million ethnicRussians live in the non-Russian republics of the former Soviet Union,the low figure for registered voters appears to indicate that relativelyfew of them have chosen to take out Russian citizenship. -- ScottParrishREMAND PRISONERS VOTE FOR ZHIRINOVSKY. Suspects in prison awaitingtrial, who unlike convicts have the right to vote, opted for VladimirZhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party of Russia, Interfax reported on18 December. According to the Interior Ministry, 30-40% of prisoners inpre-trial detention centers voted for Zhrinovsky. Women of Russia, theBeer Lovers' Party, and the Communists all got about 6-10%. Zhirinovskyhad predicted his success, saying that prisoners, like other Russians,are fed up with crime. -- Penny MorvantThis material was reprinted with permission of the OpenMedia Research Institute, a nonprofit organization with researchoffices in Prague, Czech Republic.For more information on OMRI publications,please write to:  info@omri.cz-----BEGIN PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----Version: 2.2mQCNAjCa/14AAAEEALKTqTI1BVtFs63+rV0zPyTQZ3Mi0iNPrFK0SJw71ypW0QM+medOV8X0UZaeKYg455IdB9QfC7tEi7xWZGPSiGbUxlhuN4hTOonFhIRJg2CDE3iG53OSsh2OHRyM3O0ozTnroKKoFax8Wz9wZQsrNQc5fpbx/JFqG43bm6trFGRjAAURtChOZW16ZXQgPG5lbXpldEBtYWd5YXIuc2lsaWNvbnZhbGxleS5jb20+=WggG-----END PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----
