IAN PREMIER'S PRESS OFFICE RESIGNS. After six days inoffice, Henrik Havas has resigned from his post as head of the newCommunications and Press Office at the Prime Minister's Office,Hungarian media reported. Havas accused the press of "unobjective" and"overcritical" reporting of the case of Endre Mihalyi, one of hisappointees in the office (see OMRI Daily Digest, 7 November). He deniedresponsibility, saying he could not have known that a policeinvestigation against Mihalyi was under way. Prime Minister Gyula Hornsaid he considers Havas innocent and counts on his future cooperation.All of Havas's staff members have also resigned except for officemanager Peter Szegvari, who has been asked to set up a new team by theend of November. -- Zsofia SzilagyiROMANIAN CHAMBER OF DEPUTIES AMENDS EDUCATION LAW. The Chamber ofDeputies on 7 November approved several amendments to the education law.Cristian Urse, leader of the Students' League at Bucharest University,told Romanian TV that the amendments do not meet all the students'demands. He said some taxes to which the students object have beenretained, campus premises have not been declared out of bounds forpolice authorities, and their demand for representation on theuniversities' councils and senates has been rejected. The students, Ursesaid, are now waiting for the Senate to pass its own version of theamended law. If their demands are not met in that version either, theywill resume protest actions, he warned. -- Michael ShafirHUNGARIAN TV BROADCASTS BANNED IN ROMANIA. Hungarian media on 8 Novemberreported that Romania's National Media Council has decided to banbroadcasts by Duna TV, a Hungarian satellite program on cable network.The head of the council told ethnic Hungarian deputy Ferenc Baranyi thatno license will be issued to cable television companies "for a certainperiod of time." He said that according to information received by thecouncil, Duna TV broadcasts create suspicion between ethnic minoritiesand the majority and are capable of "whipping up artificial tension." --Zsofia SzilagyiThis material was reprinted with permission of the OpenMedia Research Institute, a nonprofit organization with researchoffices in Prague, Czech Republic.For more information on OMRI publications,please write to:  info@omri.cz=====Kivonatos szemelvenyek Bodnar Daniel a Batthyany-Alapitvany szamarakeszitett napi sajtoszemlejebolA jovo evi koltsegvetes a korabbi kormanyok altal kovetettgazdasagpolitika hatarozott korrekciojat jelenti - mondta tegnap aparlamentben Bokros Lajos. A T.  Haz a penzugyminiszter expozejavalmegkezdte az 1996. evi koltsegvetesi torveny altalanos vitajat. Aminiszter hangsulyozta: meg kell teremteni a fenntarthato novekedesfelteteleit, ez azonban tovabbi atcsoportositast igenyel afogyasztastol a beruhazasok fele. A penzugyi tarca vezetoje arrol isbeszelt, hogy mielobb el kell kezdeni a szocialis rendszerek atfogoreformjat, es a raszorultsagi elvet kell ervenyesiteni. A kormany avitak ellenere tovabbra is javasolja, hogy az igenyelheto szocialisjuttatasok fuggjenek a polgarok vagyoni helyzetetol.  Bokros szerintjovore a szokasosnal is nagyobb a tet, a fo kerdes az, hogyfolytatodik-e 1996-ban is a megkezdett stabilizacio. Arrol is szolt,hogy minden elozetes varakozast felulmulva mintegy 20 milliardforinttal csokkent oktoberben a kozponti koltsegvetes hianya, amelyigy 196 milliard forintra merseklodott. A penzugyminiszter szerint apotkoltsegvetesben a privatizacios bevetelek nelkul eloiranyzottdeficitet tartani tudjak. Az ASZ elnoke, Hagelmayer Istvanfelszolalasaban arra hivta fel a figyelmet, hogy hihetetlenul nehez evkovetkezik. Ket ellenzeki vezerszonok elesen kritizalta a koltsegvetestervezetet: Kadar Bela az MDF velemenyekent a jovedelemelvonastbiralta. A koltsegvetest "hodoltsagi haracspolitikanak" nevezte, smint mondta, ez nem az orszag koltsegvetese, hanem a Jozsef nadore,aminek nyoman ezrek jajdulnak majd fel: "Lajos herceg, irgalmazznekunk!".  Kadar kijelentette, az egesz mu, ugy ahogy van, vitaraalkalmatlan. Torgyan Jozsef az FKGP velemenyekent a bevetelieloiranyzatok eltulzottsagarol, a kiadasi tetelek alatervezettsegerolbeszelt. Az SZDSZ-es Gaal Gyula partja valasztasi igeretereemlekeztetett, mondvan: az olcso allam a csaknem egymillio allamialkalmazott szamanak csokkenteset is jelentette. Keso este a parlamentelfogadta a devizarol es a biztositasrol szolo torvenyeket. EzzelMagyarorszag eleget tesz az IMF alapszabalya 8. cikkelyenek, amelybiztositja a forint konvertibilitasat (Magyar Hirlap,Nepszabadsag, Uj Magyarorszag).Figyelmezteto sztrajk kezdodik ma a Tiszai Eromu Rt. uzemeiben. ATiszai Vegyi Kombinat Rt. dolgozoi is sztrajkkeszultsegben vannak. Azerdekkepviseletek meg nem tudjak, hogy vallalataikra is vonatkozik-e avasarnapi kormanydontes (Nepszabadsag).Altalanos sztrajkot terveznek a villamosenergia-ipari szakszervezetek,amennyiben nem szuletik meg az ez evi bermegallapodas - jelentette beGal Rezso, a VDSZSZ elnoke kedden Budapesten tartottsajtotajekoztatojan. Hetfo delig varjak az APV Rt.  ajanlatat. Asztrajkbizottsag kedden a VDSZSZ szovetsegi vezetoi ulesen megalakult,es jovo hetfoig nyitva all a tobbi erintett szakszervezet elott is. Azesetleges agazati altalanos sztrajk nyolcoras lesz, es azt jelenti,hogy 25 szazalekkal visszaterhelik az aram- es hotermelo egysegeket,tehat negyedevel csokkentik a termelest. Ebbol a lakossagi fogyasztoksemmit sem fognak megerezni, az ipari fogyasztok azonban feltehetoenigen (Magyar Nemzet).A paksi atomeromu szakszervezeti altal letrehozott sztrajkbizottsagfelhaboritonak tartja, hogy a miniszterelnok es a kormany egyes tagjaiszandekosan felretajekoztatjak a kozvelemenyt, es ezzel megprobaljakaz orszag lakossagat a torveny adta jogukkal elo munkavallalok ellenhangolni. A nyilatkozat szerint nem igaz a miniszterelnok sajtobanmegjelent kijelentese, hogy Pakson 24 szazalekos volt abernovekedes. Ezzel szemben a valosag, hogy eddig 9 szazalekos volt anovekedes.A penzugyminiszter allitasaval ellentetben az eromu eredmenyeben nemervenyesul az aremeles. A paksi atomeromu sztrajkbizottsaga amegallapodas elmaradasa eseteben kezdemenyezi avillamosenergia-iparban az egyseges, altalanos sztrajk meghirdeteset(Magyar Nemzet).Feher Jozsef, a Magyar Koztisztviselok es KozalkalmazottakSzakszervezetenek ugyvezeto elnoke egy harom megyet atfogokozigazgatasi tanacskozason leszogezte: ha november 13-an nem sikerulmegallapodasra jutni a kormannyal, akar sztrajkra is keszen allnak(Magyar Hirlap).A szocialis dolgozok szakszervezete csatlakozott az egeszsegugyiekszombati demonstraciojahoz, munkafelteteleik javitasat es 35szazalekos beremelest kovetelve. A Magyar Orvosi Kamara tamogatna egyesetleges egeszsegugyi sztrajkot, bar az orvosok a sztrajkban nemkivannak reszt venni. A Honvedszakszervezet a miniszterrel folytatottkeddi targyalas utan, amely elorehaladast hozott, ugy dontott, hogyelhalasztja a hivatasos katonak novemberre tervezett demonstraciojat.December 2-an dontenek arrol, hogy megtartjak-e tiltakozomegmozdulasukat (Magyar Nemzet, Nepszabadsag).A KDNP parlamenti kepviselocsoportja hetfoi ulesen hatarozatijavaslattervezetet fogalmazott meg a part szombaton osszeulo, aszovetsegi politikarol hatarozo orszagos valasztmany szamara. Akepviselok 12:4 aranyban elfogadtak azt a dokumentumot, miszerinttartalmilag kiforratlan, ezert ido elotti az ellenzeki partok kozotti,irasban rogzitett szovetseg.  Szukseges viszont a hatekony politikaies szakmai egyuttmukodes, amelyet minden arra hajlando parttal ki kellepiteni (Nepszabadsag).A Magyar Hirlap arrol ir, hogy a Polgari Szovetseg letrehozasarairanyulo javaslatnak tekinti a KDNP vezetosege a kepviselocsoport fentismertetett hatarozattervezetet. A lap szerint a partvezetoseg es afrakcio javaslata kozott csupan annyi a kulonbseg, hogy a szigoruannegyparti egyuttmukodes helyett a kepviselocsoport az MDF-fel es aFidesszel a kisgazdak nelkul is hajlando lenne politikaiegyuttmukodesre.II. Janos Pal papa Goncz Arpad koztarsasagi elnoknek kuldott levelebenmegerositette azt a szandekat, hogy jovore Magyarorszagra latogat.Informaciok szerint a Magyar Katolikus Puspoki Kar meg ebben ahonapban hivatalosan megerositi a juniusi papalatogatas tenyet (Magyar Hirlap).Kovacs Laszlo kulugyminiszter tegnapi sajtotajekoztatojanmegerositette, hogy Horn Gyula kormanyfo november 10-en pentekenBerlinben megbeszelest folytat Vladimir Meciar szlovak kormanyfovel(Magyar Hirlap).A roman televizios es radios fohatosag, az Audiovizualis Tanacselnoke, Titus Raveica Baranyi Ferenc RMDSZ kepviselo egy hettelezelotti irasbeli interpellaciojara valaszolva kedden hivatalosanmegerositette, hogy a Duna TV adasanak kabeltelevizios tovabbitasat -a musor tartalma ellen erkezett bejelentesekre valo tekintettel -egyelore "megfigyelesi es elemzesi idoszakra" nem engedelyezi tobbromaniai varosban (Magyar Nemzet).===     Szatmari Jeno Istvan(Majdnem) Halott ujsagiro nem hazudikNagyot szola telefonlehallgatasi ugy. . .1990 karacsonyan vettem magamnak kenyelmi okokbol egy tele-fon-uzenetrogzitot. December 27-en kapcsoltam be. Aznap disznotvagtunk Lachazan. Este ertem haza. Lehallgattam a rogzitot. Rajot-tem, hogy maskeppen mukodik, mint a hasonlo keszulekek altala-ban. Ugyanis: nem vegtelenitett szalag van rajta, hanem olyan,amely minden hivasnal bemondja a gepi szoveget (30 masodpercvan, satobbi, hagyjon uzenetet), es utana fel percet ad az uzenetre.De: a gepi rogzitohangra is ravesz. Azt, amit akkor mondanak, ami-kor az uzenetet vevo szalag meg nem indul el. Es a negyedik uzenetelott, a gephang alatt valami iszonyu furcsat talaltam: dobbent noihang megjegyzi, hogy "uzenetrogzitoje van!". Az uzenet helyezisemmi. Majd ujra hivnak, es megszolal egy ferfihang: "Most, mostmegy a rogzito!" Masik ferfihang: "Vegye le a hangot, most! Fent,fent, fent, balra! Nem, nem, nem, jobbra lent!" - es ezutan Ilkeiuzenete az MDF elnoksegi uleserol. Visszahivom Ilkeit: ez meg mi?Mondja: elobb tisztazzam a postaval. Masnap reggel megteszem.Minden erintett postai forumot megkeresek: nem, nem dolgozot':senki a vonalamon. Ilkei ujabb otlete: ha a posta tagadja a vonalvizs-galatot, akkor forduljak Simon Sandor ezredeshez, aki ekkor aNemzetbiztonsagi Hivatal parancsnoka. Megteszem. Lejatszomneki telefonon at a szalagot. Igeri: delutan kijon egy embere. Ki isjon. Sarkadi Janoskent mutatkozik be. Ha a rendfokozatot jol ertet-tem, alezredes. Nevetve mondja: most beszeltem a rogzitojevel, joszovege van. Nezek ra: milyen rogzitovel? Amelyik delelott 11 otaSimon ezredes utasitasara ki van kapcsolva, a halozatbol is ki vanhuzva, es itt van a szekrenyben? Meg is mutatom. Megis allitja: an-gol nyelvu rogzito bemondta a nevem, a szamom es uzenetet kert.Lejatszom neki a sajat szalagom: magyar nyelvu gephang. Nevem,szamom nincs rajta. Uzenetet tenyleg; ker. A tobbi stimmel. Sarkadikisse elkomorodik: a szentsegit, hat a.kkor engem ki akart csapdabacsalni? Mondom: en is arra lennek kivancsi, hogyha nem az NBH,sot az NBH-t is at akarjak verni, akkor ki van rajtam? Valasz egyelorenincs.  Panaszomat hivatalbol felveszik. Honapokig vizsgaljak, es semmivalasz. Beduhodok, es junius 9-en (mar 1991-ben) a Vasarnapi Hi-rekben megjelenik az elso cikk arrol, hogy mi is van itt vegul is? Ko-veti ezt meg harom, reszben ugyane lapban, reszben a Nepszabad-sagban, es az NBH magyarazatai enyhen szolva siralmasak. Oktober20-ig tart a sajtovita. Az NBH cafol, en ujabb es ujabb adatokat tarokfel. Oktoberben uzen Sarkadi: menjek az Engels terre, egy presszo-ba, az V. keruleti onkormanyzat mellett. Ott majd lezarasul elmonddolgokat. Megyek. De nem egyedul. Az asztalnal ul volt elettarsam,Csik Rita ujsagiro. Egy masik asztalnal Docsa Bela baratom, a Nep-joleti Miniszteriumbol, es Laczko Mihaly keruleti alpolgarmester.Egy harmadik asztalnal Rita egy baratnoje. Sarkadi beszelni kezd.Probal meggyozni, hogy megiscsak postai hibaelharitokat hallot-tam. A rengeteg nalam levo nevre, adatra hivatkozva cafolom. Vegulazt mondja: nezze, nem ajanlorn, hogy tovabb bolygassa az ugyet. . .Ranezek, es kozlom: negy ernber ul itt rajtam kivul. Halljak ezt. Mitszol? Semmit. Nyugosen elmegy. . . Az ugy magyarazata "orokre ti-tok marad". Nekem nem annyira. Egy ideje hallok arrol harangozni,hogy mukodik egy parhuzamos titkosszolgalat is. De tenyleg titok-ban. Elvileg Csurka es Lezsak iranyitjak. A techrukajuk kisse amator.Eddig pletykanak hittem. Most tapasztalhatom: valakik megiscsakvannak, akik meg a nemzetbiztonsagiakat is le akartak hallgatni. . .===INTERNATIONAL BANK FOR RECONSTRUCTIONAND DEVELOPMENT (IBRD)Mr. James D. WolfensohnPresident181811 Street, N.W.Washington D.C. 20433U.S.A.Delivered by hand to theHUNGARIAN REPRESENTATION OFFICEOF THE INTERNATIONAL BANK FORRECONSTRUCTION AND DEVELOPMENTAttention:Mr. Millard LongDear Mr. wolfrnsohn,Although you are jit St beginning to get acquainted with our region and ourcountry, you have already greatly impressed us. Your radio interview, in whichyou openly admitted that you had completely forgotten to mention the countriesundergoing transition in our region in your speech delivered at the AlumniMeeting of the World Bank but added that you were coming here urgently to beable to feel exactly everything that you read in the reports since when yousaid, "... in my new position I have to evaluate each piece of informationdifferently than before", it reflected a sincere, deeply humane way ofthinking.This interview encouraged us to turn to you directly, in an open letter. TheIMF letter published recently gave the impression it was also written on behalfof the World Bank ("... we in the Fund, together with many others in theintenational community...") and it is widely known that as long asno agreement has been reached with the IMF, no contracts can be signed withthe World Bank.We have been led to write this letter by our conviction that we must notconclude an agreement with the terms and conditions stipulated by the IMF,as they are not only impossible to fulfil, but also contradict the IMF Charterenacted in Hungary.This charter stipulates that with its entire policy and with all its decisionsthe IMF should fully benefit the increase in employment and real income in ourcountry.In our opinion, the expectations of the IMF in Hungary contradict the WorldBank Charter as well, which binds the organisation to promote the improvementof living standards and working conditions and the development of the means ofproduction in a member country with all its decisions, giving special attentionto business relations. To enable the organisation directed by you to complywith these prolislons, we need to sign an agreement with the lMF whichsupports the development of the Hungarian economy and the quality of Hungarianpeople's lives.Hungary has been a member of both organisations since 1982. If we study theoutput and employment indices of Hungarian industry and agriculture, thecontinuous decline during the past 5 years in these areas is not only striking,but even bewildering. In his letter, Mr. Massimo Russo, Director of European IDepartment, summed up the IMF requirements for 1996 and 1997 in thefollowing five points:i)   Net foreign indebtedness should be reduced in the following two     budgetary years, with the current account deficit brought below USD 2     billion.ii)  The consolidated state budget, including the social security fund, should     be held to a deficit below 4% of the GDP.iii) Competitivcncss should be improved by wage restraint and inflation     shoud be reduced to an annual rate of 10% by the last quarter of 1996.iv)  Stringent monetary and credit policies with interest rates being allowed      to decline in pace with market expectations of inflation, but not forced      down by the monetary policy actions taken by the National Bank of Hungary.v)   The reduction of foreign indebtedness and the restructuring of the     economy by rapidly privatising our state-owned companies and banks. In     addition to this, the number of budgetary institutions and their staff     level should also be reduced, and social security should be restructured.According to Mr. Massimo Russo, this is the only possible economic policy to"realise our shared objectives".Whether our objectives are really shared and whether we have the same share ofsuccess or failure, we do not want to discuss now. But we must consider if theconditions can be fulfilled, if they are advisable, that is if they are reallysuitable for facilitating the long-term stability of Hungary and the balance ofthe internatiotial financial system through this. We are convinced that theanswer is no, due to the following reasons:concerning i)    The country's net foreign indebtedness is growing at anincreasing pace. According to the latest report published by the National Bankof Hungary, the net state indebtedness increased by USD 5 billion and the grossstate indebtedness by USD 6.5 billion to USD 32.2 billion during the l2 monthspreceding May 1995. (70.5% of the gross indebtedness is owed by the NationalBank of Hungary, 6% by the Hungarian Government, the remaining part bycommercial banks and companies.)The IMF expects that there should be an appreciable reduction in net foreignindebtedness, or in other words, the current exponential growth should changeinto a decrease. This change should take place first of all at the NationalBank of Hungary, and this is not hopeless. During the year which passed betweenMay 1994 and May 1995, gross indebtedness increased by USD 4.7 billion due tothe change in cross rates alone. If a vast amount like this can be lost onexchange rate changes and currency structure, maybe similar amounts can also bewon itt this way. According to the latest directive issued by the NationalBank of Hungary, all information relevant to the structure of our indebtednessand reserves, the changes therein, and the decisions relating to it, shall bekept confidential for 20 years, so we are not in a position to give advice.Neveitheless, the IMF and the World Bank have detailed data at their disposalfrom the compulsoty supply of information, So it is you who can makepreliminary calculations and estimates.The USD 4.7 billion increase in our indebtedness caused by cross rate changesequals 44% of the export revenues realised from the supply of goods andservices in 1994, so it can hardly be covered by any intensive export growth.Making another comparison, the atnount of the loss suffered from cross ratechanges is higher than the total 1994 budget revenue from personal incometaxes, and all sorts of corporate taxes and customs duties. Consequently, thebusiness sector is unable to stop increasing indebtedness either from exportgrowth or from domestic activities. Much sooner the Central Bank with itscurrency transactions hidden from the public.The Hungarian budget predicts a total income of HUF 250 billion (approximatelyUSD 2 billion) from privatisation in 1995 and 1996. This amount is alsoinsufficient to reduce our indebtedness, it can only cover our on debtservicing for a few months. Any significant growth in the pace of workingcapital imports would fall behind the growth of interest payments.Bearing in mind the above, may we take the liberty to ask you, the President ofthe World Bank, the director of many thousands of well-trained experts, to provide us with information about the factual basis of the IMF indebtednessreduction targets, publishing the relevant calculations in details. This request is based on the resolution passed by this year's Annual Meetings of thetwo financial organisations, according to which, enhanced publicity shouldbe given to the financial processes taking place im member countries.concerning ii) The IMF expects that the consolidated state budget of 1996and 1997, including the social security fund, should be held to a deficit below4% of GDP. This expectation is based on the assumption that the state budgetdeficit is caused by excess consumption which leads to an increase in importsand, consequently, to an incerease in our external indebtedness. In our opinionthis concept is incorrect. The primary balance of the Hungarian state budget ispositive, that is, the budget has more revenue than expenditure. The deficit iscaused by interest payments, of which only a minor part is channelled to theeconomy, and an even smaller portion creates real interest which feedsconsumption. Calculations made with real interest show a deficit of only 1 or 2% of GDP for the past few years, far less than the ratio accepted in developedcountries. The major part of the interest payments effected by the state budgetflows to the National Bank of Hungary and then abroad, obviously catering forno demand whatsoever domestically.The Hungarian Parliament will start discussing the 1996 state budget in a fewdays. As the amount of our debt servicing figured in the proposed budget evenwithout the repayment of principal - is considerably higher than any otherbudget expenditure item, its impact on the deficit is dominant not only in1996, but in the following years as well.Under these circumstances it need not be proved that it is not the socialsecurity, public welfare, cultural and other expenditure that counts as regardsthe state budget deficit, but our debt servicing and the impact of the relevantmonetary policies. That is why we are asking you to disclose the detailedpreliminary calculations relating to the structure of the GDP-proportionatebudget deficit, so that the 4% ratio expected by the IMF, with its provedreality, could become acceptable to society.concerning iii) The IMF expects wage restraint as, according to its letter,the state budget deficit limit can be complied with only in this way, and thisis expected to help bring down inflation to 10% within a year. In our opinion, the direct demand restraining effect of reduced real wages effects inflationfar less than the burden of our debt servicing and privatisation. During thepast few years, prices were increased not as a result of additional purchasingpower, but in most cases due to central measures (the increase of energyprices, public transport fees, taxes, etc.). It was the World Bank whichrequired the increase in household electricity prices. Consequently, Hungarianinflation is not fed by an excess demand, but by transferring the burdens ofthe state budget and the National Bank of Hungary. The relatively highpurchasing power that exists among the buyers of state bonds and luxuriousarticles, are not among these wage earners.Reduced real wages will also result in deteriorating exports. A growing part ofpioducts sold abroad is based ott cheap commission work or is of the raw-material level. The number of goods with higher added value decreases with theelimination of better trained workers. Also, the place of quality goodsmanufactured in Hungary has been taken by imported articles. In the first fivemonths of 1995, according to a report published by the National Bank ofHungary, Hungarian exports increased by 1.5% while imports rose by 7-9%,although our deficit was very high already last year. Within exports,commission work increased by 20% and the export of raw materials and spareparts grew, so the sales of more sophisticated products obviously went down.Bearing in mind the above, wage restraint together with the further decrease ofadded value generates an increase in external indebtedness as well, thusincreasing inflation instead of reducing it.To get a clear picture, it is essential that the IMF disclose its detailedcalculations about the actual effects of the expected fall in real wages,includiiig the export and import dimensions as well. If the 10% inflation levelscheduled for the end of 1996 is a realistic expectation, then inflationaryexpectations could really be curbed and public opinion calmed by publishing therelevant detailed calculations. Also, the provision of authentic and objectiveinformation would contribute to enhancing the prestige of the world's financialorganisations.concerning iv) Stritigent monetary and crediting policies have kept interestrates at a high level so far. This credit restraint hits the economy now, butan indebted state and central bank seem to be interested in this as this istheir main instrument in managing external and internal debts for the timebeing.There is no doubt that the central bank materially influences creditingpolicies evetywhere. The National Bank of Hungary (NBH) has proved this abilityby reducing the interest rate on discount treasury bills from 30% to 10% withinthe few months preceding the bank consolidation agreement of April 1993. Thisis the interest to be paid on bank consolidation state bonds with a maturity of20 years. NBIHI "stimulated" the government to assume the entire loss ofcommercial banks by this seemingly low rate of interest. But during the fewmonths following the consolidation agreement - which was actively promoted andhelped by the IMF and the World Bank - the interest rate of treasury bills,which must now be paid after the bank consolidation state bonds as well, roseto exceed 30% again. Such a slim "V" interest rate diagram cannot be generatedby market mechanisms.The NBH needs high revenues because of debt servicing. It collects theserevenues from two major sources: the yield of state bonds (at a cost to thebudget and the taxpayer) and the business sector. The NBH itself writes that"..  with the help of relatively low-interest-bearing, high compulsory reserveratio it must tax the economy implicitly via the banking sector ...". This"taxation" increases the compulsory reserve ratio to be deposited with the NBHfrom the inteinationally accepted 1 or 2% to its tenfold and - as the NBH doesnot pay realistic interest after these reserves, thus generates losses at thecommercial banks. This fact compels banks to further increase the interest tobe paid by entrepreneurs. Therefore, the number of clients who can raise HUFloans is reduced and the number of those who go bankrupt as a result of theirloans is increased. At the same time banks with part foreign ownership,fulfilling their reserve obligation in a foreign currency, receive a realisticrate of interest and thus enjoy a competitive advantage over domesticcommercial banks. As a result of this, in the long run local banks will losetheir markets and foreign enterprises with their funds in foreign currencieswill become dominant. This process will also increase imports and worsen theforeign exchange balance. Thousands of jobs will be lost due to interest rateskept at a high level, entrepreneurs will be permanently replaced byadministrators in bankruptcy and instead of creating jobs the main managerialactivity will be crisis management. Foreign investment in cheap commissionwork will be considered more valuable since a higher level of productionbecomes impossible.Farmers have no access to realistic bank loans either, so they receive credit from their crop buyers or suppliers. This distorts prices and takes away theincome which could be realised by agriculture and worsens living conditions invillages. In the end budget expenditure rises, investment, infrastructuraldevelopments and related employment are not accomplished, and the real incomeof agriculture flows abroad with cheap raw materials.The spreading effect of a series of bankruptcies hinder tlte repayment ofotherwise good loans, and it morally relieves the debtors from theirobligations. In this way commercial banks are weakened, they need further andfurther state rescue operations, and as a result the bonds market seems to beexpanding. But in reality a bogus economy is generated. In the end, Hungarianbanks will be driven out of the business sector, they will trade with eachorher, the NBH and the state. They will try to earn their living without realbusiness performance. During the privatisation of banks we can hardly expect afavorable price for the weakened banks and their market shares.Bearing in mind the above, we would highly appreciate the IMF, by analysing thedata undoubtedly available to it and with its quantified forecasts, proving thebasis of a radical fall in inflation, giving special attention to the fact thatthe lMF itself expects the central bank to maintain the present level of itsinterest rates.concerning v) The encouragement of privatisation has been recurring for yearswith the frequent statement that any private owner is better than theHungarian state. This statement has not been critically analysed with 5 yearsof privatisation experience already behind us. But Hungarian citizens arebeginning to refuse more and more definitely the rushed and secret sales onthe basis of their own experience. And it was exactly the World Bank expertswho proposed a careful, experimental and continuously evaluated process.It could be seen from this analysis that a major part of the foreign capitalarrives only for speculative purposes, seeking and finding huge and invisibleincomes, settling only for a short stay. In many cases foreign capital buysonly market shares, even if it promises developments during privatisation.Entire industrial branches were bought by foreign groups creating monopoliesin the domestic market. The population, unlike state admimistration andprivatisation consultants, very much realises the negative consequences. Thenew foreign owners often liquidate local processing, obtaining an advantage bybetter utilising their West European or overseas capacities, thus consideringour country only as a market.A year ago, Mr. Clinton encouraged American capital to be invested in Hungaryby saying that they could create jobs in America by doing so. This is all rightfrom his point of view, but, without compensating meehanisms, this leads to thedecline of the Hungarian economy. The product and capital export subsidiesapplied by the developed countries are missing in Hungary. Moreover, the IMFexpectations are directed at the elimination of the still existing ones, sothere is no reciprocity.For example, the state had reconstructed 5 vegetable oil processing plantsusing a World Bank loan prior to privatisation. But now the new ownerdismantles and liquidates these up-to-date plants while the foreign currencyloan raised for the reconstniction must be repaid, by the Hungarian state. TheWorld Bank does not object to this procedure, although it contradicts the loanagreement. Instead of exporting the processed goods, the export of cheapsunflower seeds and the import of expensive soya beans becomes characteristic.As a result, animal breeding and meat exports are ruined, and domesticconsumption is reduced. As opposed to the privatisation income, enough to coveronly a few days of our interest burden, the Hungarian economy must endurecontinuous, large, direct and indirect losses. Consequently, the realobjectives of foreign capital coming to Hungary are the important factors, andnot the amount of incoming capital.Because of the lack of domestic credit, and the availability of foreignfinancing, it is gradually more to the interest of wholesalers to orientthemselves to import. Big European retailer chains, that bought up shopsselling everyday items, thus sell to the public imported goods in an everincreasing percentage. It is understandable that they usetheir existing logistics, their ordering channels, they are committed totheir previous suppliers, thus they are reluctant to bother with thelocal suppliers, poorer packaging. Thus, production in Hungary isshrinking, the balance of trade in hard currency worsens and the inflationgrows.Although there is some experience about the impact of privatisationof the so-called natural monopolies (bottled gas, telecommunication,etc.) studies on how they impact on retail prices and transfer of income ispresently still lacking. At this time, the gross distributers of energy(piped gas, electricity suppliers), in the lack of a public evaluation ofearlier privatisation actions, public opinion awaits these privatisationdecisions anxiously, fearing an increase in prices which would threaten thequality of life very severely. The number of people demanding the refusal ofsuch decisions is continuously increasing. Privatisation forced through withoutthe support of the society may give rise to new tensions.It is a well-known effect of privatisation that the foreign capital rises its property obtained during privatisation - by underpriced exports and overpricedimports - for practically transferring its income without taxation abroad andis able to operate its Hungarian interest even at a loss. It finances the lossfrom abroad, but applies for subsidies here in Hungary. Thousands of jobs werelost in this way and the social maintenance of entire towns became a statecrisis-management task. If the IMF urges privatisation, it should objectivelyevaluate these positive and negative impacts and publish the results.Dear Mr. Wolfensohn,During your visit you may meet with wide-spread social restlessness anddeveloping local and branch snikes. The police are strengthening themselves tobe able to "handle" the demonstrations, but there is not enough money to combatthe black economy and criminals. Large groups of our society are at a loss tounderstand the critical processes, having no prospects at all in their ruinedsocial situation and health condition. The Hungarian-born and educated Americanengineer, who was awarded the Nobel prize last year, saw the breaking point ineducation - like so many other people -. but today already primary education isheavily burdened. The Hungarian-born and educated professor of economics,who was awarded the Nobel prize also last year was completely at a loss tothe economic policies in Hungary.  It appears that these processes areill understood both by the men in the street and by the Nobel laureateprofessor. Thus, we respectfully ask you and those thousands of experts whowork under you direction, not to try to convince the public by ambiguousgeneralities of the terms of "structural reform", "Bokros-package", "rapidprivatisation" , as these slogans remind people of the official reasoning inthe worst times of the planned economy. Instead, you should convince theHungarian population that the economic policy required by the IMF isappropriate by disclosing the concrete facts and preliminary calculations. Inour opinion a fair agreement may be concluded only on the basis ofprovably feasible and suitable criteria.Budapest, 26 October 1995.  Sincerely yours,Dr Laszlo AndoreconomistDr. Magdolna Csatheconomist, university professorDr. Mihaly Fecskeeconomist, university professorDr. Erzsebet Gidaieconomist, university professorDr. Sandor Kopatsyeconomist, candidateDr. Janos Kovacseconomist, research workerKaroly LoranteconomistDr. Miklos Mandeleconomist, university professorDr. Jozsef Mocsaryeconomist, candidateDr. Pongrac NagyeconomistTibor NemetheconomistDr. Kalman Pecsiuniversity professorIstvan SiklakyeconomistDr. Gyorgy Szakolczaiuniversity professorDr. Tamas SzitaeconomistDr. Barna Talasdoctor of political scienceIstvan Vargadipl. mechanical engineer-----BEGIN PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-----Version: 2.2mQCNAjCa/14AAAEEALKTqTI1BVtFs63+rV0zPyTQZ3Mi0iNPrFK0SJw71ypW0QM+medOV8X0UZaeKYg455IdB9QfC7tEi7xWZGPSiGbUxlhuN4hTOonFhIRJg2CDE3iG53OSsh2OHRyM3O0ozTnroKKoFax8Wz9wZQsrNQc5fpbx/JFqG43bm6trFGRjAAURtChOZW16ZXQgPG5lbXpldEBtYWd5YXIuc2lsaWNvbnZhbGxleS5jb20+=WggG-----END PGP PUBLIC KEY BLOCK-