<html>
<head>
<title>Summary of Proposed Changes to GA Rules for Haz. Waste
Management</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h3>SUMMARY OF PROPOSED CHANGES TO<br>
GEORGIA RULES FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE MANAGEMENT<br>
</h3>
<p>Copies of the Federal Registers referenced in this document
are available at most public and regional libraries. Full copies
of desired Federal Registers are available from the Hazardous
Waste Management Branch Office at (404) 656-7802. Copying cost
will be added for multiple copies.<br>
<br>
DATE<br>
VOL:PAGE NO.<br>
AFFECTED 40 CFR<br>
SECTIONS<br>
<br>
DESCRIPTION<br>
</p>
<p>July 11, 1995<br>
60: 35,705<br>
264.314, 265.314<br>
Adds a test method to demonstrate that sorbents used to solidify
hazardous waste are non-biodegradable.<br>
December 11, 1995<br>
60: 63,431<br>
124 Subpart B, 124.31, 124.32, 124.33, 270.2, 270.14, 270.30,
270.62, 270.66<br>
Improves the permitting process for facilities that store, treat,
or dispose of hazardous wastes by providing earlier opportunities
for public involvement and expanding public access to information
throughout the permitting process and the operational lives of
hazardous waste facilities.<br>
</p>
<p>March 26, 1996<br>
61: 13,106<br>
261.4<br>
Corrects the text of a regulatory exclusion from the definition
of solid waste for recovered oil which is inserted into the
petroleum refining process. This corrected rule conditions the
exclusion of recovered oil on that oil being reinserted into the
petroleum refining process at a point where that process removes
or will remove at least some contaminants.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>EXHIBIT AA-1&quot; <br>
April 8, 1996<br>
61: 15,597 <br>
268 Subpart A, 268.1, 268.2, 268.3, 268.7, 268.8, 268.9,
268.10-.12, 268.39, 268.40, 268.42, 268.48, 268 Appendix XI<br>
Promulgates treatment stan-dards for hazardous wastes from the
production of carbamate pesticides and from primary aluminum
production under its Land Disposal Restriction program. It also
amends the treatment standards for hazardous wastes that exhibit
the characteristic of reactivity. This rule also begins the
process of amending existing treatment standards for wastewaters
which are hazardous because they display the characteristic of
ignitability, corrosivity, reactivity, or toxicity. These wastes
are sometimes treated in lagoons whose ultimate discharge is
regulated under the Clean Water Act, and sometimes injected into
deep wells which are regulated under the Safe Drinking Water Act.
Prior to this rule, the treatment standards for these wastes
required only removal of the characteristic property. These
revised standards require treatment, not only to remove the
characteristic, but also to treat any underlying hazardous
constituents which may be present in the wastes, therefore,
minimizing threats from exposure to hazardous constituents which
may potentially migrate from these lagoons or wells. This rule
also codifies its existing Enforcement Policy that combustion of
inorganic wastes is an impermissible form of treatment because
hazardous constituents are being diluted rather than effectively
treated.<br>
</p>
<p>April 8, 1996 <br>
61: 15,662<br>
268 Subpart A, 268.1, 268.3, 268.39, 268.40<br>
Withdraws portions of revised treatment standards for hazardous
wastewaters that exhibit the characteristic of ignitability,
corrosivity, reactivity, or toxicity. Withdraws provisions of the
Land Disposal Program Flexibility Act of 1996 which provides that
the wastes in question are no longer prohibited from land
disposal so long as they are not hazardous wastes at the point
they are land disposed. <br>
April 12, 1996<br>
61: 16,309<br>
261.6, 262.10, 262.53, 262.56, 262.58, 262 Subpart H, 262.80,
262.81, 262.82, 262.83, 262.84, 262.85, 262.86, 262.87, 262.88,
262.89, 263.10, 263.20, 264.12, 264.71, 265.12, 265.71, 266.70,
273.20, 273.40, 273.56, 273.70<br>
Modifies procedural controls governing the export and import of
hazardous waste. Harmonizes hazardous waste rules with new OECD
rules to increase efficiency. Identifies wastes under the
Resources Conservation and Recover Act (RCRA) subject to a
graduated system of procedural and substantive controls when they
move across national borders within the Organization for Economic
Development (OECD) for recovery. This rule seeks to prevent or
minimize the possibility of such wastes being abandoned or
otherwise illegally handled and applies only to exporters and
importers of RCRA hazardous wastes destined for recovery in OCED
countries (except for Canada and Mexico). <br>
<br>
April 30, 1996<br>
61: 19,117<br>
268, 268.39<br>
Corrects errors giving incorrect dates in the April 8, 1996 final
rule.<br>
</p>
<p>June 28, 1996 <br>
61: 33,682<br>
268 Subpart A, 268.1, 268.2, 268.3, 268.39, 268.40, 268.48<br>
Corrects technical errors in the April 8, 1996 final rule.<br>
August 26, 1996<br>
268 Subpart D, 268.40, 268.48<br>
Revises the carbamate waste treatment standards for one year by
allowing carbamate wastes to be treated either by any technology
which achieves the constituent concentration levels promulgated
in the Phase III rule, or by treatment technologies specified in
this final rule as alternative treatment standards. This rule
also suspends the requirement to treat carbamate waste
constituents when they are expected to be present in ignitable,
corrosive, reactive or toxic hazardous wastes as Aunderlying
hazardous constituents.@ EPA believes these temporary alternative
treatment standards will assure that carbamate wastes are
adequately treated prior to land disposal, while providing time
for analytic chemical standards to be developed.<br>
<br>
<br>
In addition to incorporating the above Federal Registers, Rule
391-3-11-.19 AStandards for Waste Mercury-Containing Lamps@ has
been added to give an alternative set of management standards to
waste mercury-containing lamps, in lieu of regulation under 40
CFR Parts 260-272. By adding these standards to our rules,
handlers and generators are encouraged to recycle rather than
dispose of waste mercury-containing lamps. Waste
mercury-containing lamps recycled in accordance with this rule
are exempted from most hazardous waste handling requirements.<br>
<br>
Mercury-containing lamps are defined as any type of high or low
pressure lighting device that is unprocessed, contains mercury
and generates light through the discharge of electricity either
directly or indirectly through a fluorescing coating. The term
waste mercury-containing lamp includes fluorescent lamps, mercury
lamps, metal halide lamps and high pressure sodium lamps.<br>
<br>
A mercury containing lamp becomes a waste on the date it is
discarded or is permanently removed from its fixture and can no
longer be used to provide lighting. </p>
</body>
</html>
