<html>
<head>
<title>Hazardous Waste Q&amp;A</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body background="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/whttxtr1.jpg"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p>[ <a href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/index.htm">Home</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/news.htm">What's New</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/toc.htm">TOC</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/feedback.htm">Feedback</a> | <a
href="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/search.htm">Search</a> ]</p>
<h1 align="center"><img
src="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/images/epd.gif" align="left"
hspace="0" width="100" height="100"><b>Frequently Asked Questions</b></h1>
<hr width="80%">
<p><u><br clear="left">
</u><br>
Q/A Key Words: HSRA, IEUBK, Lead, Risk Reduction Standards<br>
<br>
Regulatory Area: RCRA_____ CERCLA_____ HSRA__<u>X</u>___ Other
(specify)_____<br>
<br>
<strong>QUESTION</strong>:<br>
<br>
Lead is often a chemical associated with a release at sites
listed on the Georgia Hazardous Sites Inventory (HSI). Is the
Federal EPA's Integrated Exposure Uptake Biokinetic (IEUBK) model
allowed to be used in the determination of lead clean-up values
under HSRA risk reduction standard types 1-5 (rule 391-3-19-.07)
at these sites?<br>
<br>
ANSWER:<br>
<br>
Currently, the HSRA risk reduction standards do not allow for the
use of the IEUBK model in determining clean-up values for lead at
HSI sites. In order for the model to be used for determination of
compliance with one of the risk reduction standards, the rule
would have to be changed. <br>
<br>
<br>
Compiled by: Ken Mitchell<br>
<br>
Date: 8/28/95<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>Q/A Key Words: PCBs, Aroclors<br>
<br>
Regulatory Area: RCRA__X___ CERCLA_____ HSRA__X___ Other
(specify)_____<br>
<br>
<strong>QUESTION: </strong><br>
<br>
When performing risk based calculations for purposes of complying
with RCRA or HSRA requirements, how should polychlorinated
biphenyls (PCBs) be considered?<br>
<br>
ANSWER:<br>
<br>
PCBs are a group of man-made organic chemicals that contain 209
individual compounds (known as congeners) with the following
general structure:<u><img src="images/hazqa1.gif"
alt="PCB Structure" align="right" hspace="0" width="559"
height="278"></u><u><br>
</u></p>
<p><u><br clear="right">
</u>where carbons 2-6 and 2'-6' are chlorinated to various
degrees. <br>
<br>
PCBs generally enter the environment by use of commercial
mixtures of congeners. Some commercial PCB mixtures are known in
the US by their industrial trade name, Aroclor. The Aroclors are
identified by a four-digit numbering code in which the first two
digits indicate that the parent molecule is biphenyl (i.e., 12
carbons) and the last two digits indicate the chlorine content by
weight percent. Thus, Aroclor 1242 is a chlorinated biphenyl
mixture of varying amounts of mono- through heptachlorinated
homologs with an average chlorine content of 42%. The exception
to this code is Aroclor 1016, which contains mono- through
hexachlorinated homologs with an average chlorine content of 41%.<br>
<br>
The current version of EPA's Integrated Risk Information System
(IRIS) contains the following toxicity values for various Aroclor
mixtures:</p>
<p align="center"><strong>IRIS RfDs and Slope Factors<br>
for Various Aroclors</strong></p>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <th align="left" width="33%">
        <p align="center"><strong>Aroclor</strong></p>
        </th>
        <th align="left" width="33%">
        <p align="center"><strong>Chronic Oral RfD (mg/kg-d)</strong></p>
        </th>
        <th align="left" width="34%">
        <p align="center"><strong>Carcinogenic Oral Slope Factor
        (mg/kg-d)*1</strong></p>
        </th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">1016</p>
        </td>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">7 x 10-5</p>
        </td>
        <td width="34%">
        <p align="center">NV</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">1248</p>
        </td>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">NV</p>
        </td>
        <td width="34%">
        <p align="center">NV</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">1254</p>
        </td>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">2 x 10-5</p>
        </td>
        <td width="34%">
        <p align="center">NV</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">1260*</p>
        </td>
        <td width="33%">
        <p align="center">NV</p>
        </td>
        <td width="34%">
        <p align="center">7.7 (B2; Probable Human Carcinogen)</p>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>NV = No Value<br>
*IRIS provides a slope factor for &quot;Polychlorinated
Biphenyls.&quot; However, the critical study upon which this
slope factor is based used Aroclor 1260.<br>
<br>
EPA's Health Effects Assessment Summary Tables (HEAST) also
provides a subchronic oral RfD for Aroclor 1254 of 5 x 10-5
mg/kg-d (this subchronic RfD is a modification of the chronic
oral RfD).<br>
<br>
When making risk based calculations for purposes of complying
with the RCRA or HSRA requirements, EPD has chosen to be
conservative in its evaluation of PCBs. Thus, EPD will generally
consider the sum of all PCBs present in an exposure scenario and
apply the most stringent RfD and slope factor available. The most
stringent RfD is the chronic oral RfD for Aroclor 1254. Aroclor
1260 is the only mixture for which there is a slope factor;
therefore, it is used by default.<br>
<br>
If sufficient information is available to determine the amounts
of various Aroclor mixtures present in an exposure scenario, EPD
may consider the application of an alternate RfD strategy. For
example, if it is known that Aroclor 1016 was the only source of
environmental PCB contamination at a particular facility, then
the RfD for this mixture (rather than the more restrictive RfD
for Aroclor 1254) may be used. In any event, EPD will generally
require an assessment of the carcinogenic risk posed by the sum
of all PCBs present and using the slope factor for Aroclor 1260. <br>
<br>
EPD may modify this strategy as additional appropriate,
peer-reviewed scientific data become available for PCBs.<br>
<br>
Compiled by: Kenneth Mitchell, Ph.D.<br>
<br>
Date: 2/20/96</p>
<p>1. Toxicological Profile for Selected PCBs (Aroclor-1260,
-1254, -1248, -1242, -1232,<br>
-1221, and -1016), US Department of Health and Human Services,
Public Health Service, Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease
Registry (TP-92/16), April 1993. </p>
<p>2. February 1996.</p>
<p>3. Health Effects Assessment Summary Tables, FY-1995 Annual,
USEPA Office of Solid Waste and Emergency Response
(EPA/540/R-95/036; 9200.6-303 (95-1)), May 1995.</p>
<hr>
<p>&#160;</p>
<p>Q/A Key Words: Provisional Reference Values, NCEA, SHRTSC<br>
<br>
Regulatory Area: RCRA_____ CERCLA_____ HSRA__X___ Other
(specify)_____<br>
<br>
<strong>QUESTION:</strong><br>
<br>
The National Center for Environmental Assessment (NCEA) provides
provisional Reference Doses (RfDs), Reference Concentrations
(RfCs) and Slope Factors (SFs) for a number of chemicals which do
not have a value in EPA's Integrated Risk Information System
(IRIS) or EPA's Health Effects Assessment Summary Tables (HEAST).
Can these provisional values be used for purposes of complying
with the Georgia Hazardous Site Response Act (HSRA) corrective
action rules (chapter 391-3-19)? <br>
<br>
<br>
ANSWER:<br>
<br>
For purposes of complying with the HSRA corrective action rules,
the order of preference for selecting toxicity values is
described in the language at the bottom of Appendix III, Table 3
of rule 391-3-19-.07, thus:<br>
<br>
Values are to be taken from the current version of IRIS or, if
not listed in IRIS, from the current version of HEAST. Where data
are not available from IRIS or HEAST and appropriate,
peer-reviewed data are otherwise available, values may be derived
using the procedures described in RAGS, Part A and in
consultation with the Director. <br>
<br>
The current version of HEAST (FY-95) identifies substances for
which publicly available toxicity values are available from the
NCEA. Specifically, for certain substances, HEAST does not list a
toxicity value, but directs the reader to call the Superfund
Health Risk Technical Support Center (SHRTSC) located at the
NCEA. The SHRTSC will provide a provisional toxicity value to
callers upon request. EPD considers these provisional values
equivalent to being explicitly listed in HEAST and, as such,
requires their use in complying with the HSRA corrective action
rules.<br>
<br>
Table I lists the provisional RfDs, RfCs, and SFs that are
currently available to the public from the SHRTSC. These values
are subject to change and the most current, publicly available
provisional values are to be used when showing compliance with a
risk reduction standard(s).</p>
<p align="center"><font size="4"><strong>TABLE I</strong></font></p>
<table border="1" width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="25%"><font size="4"><strong>Regulated
        Substance</strong></font></td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"><font size="4"><strong>RfD
        (o) (mg/kg-day)</strong></font></td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"><font size="4"><strong>RfC(mg/m3)</strong></font></td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"><font size="4"><strong>SF
        ((mg/kg-day)-1)</strong></font></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="25%">Benzene</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"></td>
        <td align="center" width="25%">6 x 10-2 (s)</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="25%">Bromomethane </td>
        <td align="center" width="25%">5 x 10-3 (s)</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%">2 x 10-1 (s)</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="25%">Chlorobenzene</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%">*</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%">2 x 10-1 (s)</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="25%">Chloroform</td>
        <td align="center" width="25%"></td>
