<p>* - HEAST incorrectly identifies a subchronic RfD as being
available from NCEA<br>
** - While HEAST does not identify it, this toxicity value is
publicly available from NCEA<br>
*** - HEAST incorrectly identifies a subchronic RfC as being
available from NCEA<br>
(c) - Chronic<br>
(s) - Subchronic<br>
(o) - Oral<br>
(i) - Inhalation<br>
Compiled by: Clifford A. Opdyke, Ph.D.<br>
<br>
Date: 5/21/96</p>
<p>1. NCEA also has provisional values for certain substances
which are available only to Federal Superfund Toxicologists
(i.e., they are not publicly available). Since these values are
not accessible to the public, EPD is not generally requiring
their use.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<hr>
<p>Q/A Key Words: Site Specific Exposure Factors<br>
<br>
Regulatory Area: RCRA_____ CERCLA_____ HSRA__<u>X</u>___ Other
(specify)_____<br>
<br>
<strong>QUESTION: </strong><br>
<br>
When performing risk based calculations for purposes of complying
with HSRA Type 2 and Type 4 risk reduction standards, what is
meant by the phrase &quot;site-specific exposure factors?&quot;<br>
<br>
<strong>ANSWER:</strong><br>
<br>
To be eligible for a Type 2 or a Type 4 risk reduction standard,
responsible parties must take site-specific circumstances into
account when calculating acceptable concentrations using the soil
and groundwater equations from RAGS Part B. With respect to the
aforementioned equations, the particular circumstances of a site
are embodied in the &quot;site-specific exposure factors.&quot;<br>
<br>
EPD interprets the phrase &quot;site-specific exposure
factors&quot; to encompass the two separate categories of
site-specific circumstances outlined in I and II below. To be
eligible for either a Type 2 or Type 4 risk reduction standard,
the responsible party must comply with the requirements of I and
II. <br>
<br>
I. Site Receptors - For all Type 2 and Type 4 risk reduction
standard determinations, soil and groundwater calculations must
take into account the human receptors at the site under both
current and reasonably anticipated future uses of the site
[guidance on determining reasonably anticipated future land use
can be found in Land Use in the CERCLA Remedy Selection Process,
USEPA (OSWER Directive Number 9355.7-04), May 25, 1995.] <br>
<br>
For example, a residential area inhabited by children and adults
must consider both of these receptors. Calculations for children
must be performed separately from those for adults (i.e., the use
of age-adjusted soil or groundwater ingestion factors is not
allowed). The risk reduction standard based on cancer/non-cancer
effects will be the least of the calculated values.<br>
<br>
II. RAGS Part B Equation Variables - Equation variables (such as
exposure duration, exposure frequency, body weight, ingestion
rate, etc.) are to be derived as follows (this is also the order
of preference):<br>
<br>
a. Use of site-specific data. The responsible party is encouraged
to derive site-specific data for equation variables. (EPD may
consider data available for the local geographic area in which
the site is located in lieu of site-specific data, but only if a
strong argument can be made that such data is reflective of
actual site conditions.)<br>
<br>
b. Use of default values. In the absence of site-specific data,
standard default values shall be used. For exposure variables,
acceptable sources of standard default values include:<br>
<br>
Standard Default Exposure Factors, Interim Final, USEPA (OSWER
Directive No. 9285.6-03), March 25, 1991.<br>
<br>
Exposure Factors Handbook, Internal Draft, NCEA-W-005, May 1995
[Update to Exposure Factors Handbook, USEPA (EPA/600/8-89/043),
May 1989].<br>
<br>
Specifically, EPD will generally accept the following standard
exposure variable defaults for the three most commonly
anticipated receptors; namely, resident children, resident
adults, and full-time facility workers:<br>
</p>
<table width="100%">
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">Parameters</td>
        <td width="33%">Definitions (Units)</td>
        <td width="34%">Values</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">BW</td>
        <td width="33%">Body weight (kg)</td>
        <td width="34%">70 - resident adult<br>
        15 - resident child<br>
        70 - facility worker</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">AT</td>
        <td width="33%">Averaging time (yr)</td>
        <td width="34%">70 - carcinogens, all receptors<br>
        (Equals ED for non-carcinogens, all receptors)</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">EF</td>
        <td width="33%">Exposure frequency (days/yr)</td>
        <td width="34%">350 - resident adult<br>
        350 - resident child<br>
        250 - facility worker</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">ED</td>
        <td width="33%">Exposure duration (yr)</td>
        <td width="34%">30 - resident adult<br>
        6 - resident child<br>
        25 - facility worker</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">IRw</td>
        <td width="33%">Daily water ingestion rate (liter/day)</td>
        <td width="34%">2 - resident adult<br>
        1 - resident child<br>
        1 - facility worker</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">IRsoil</td>
        <td width="33%">Soil ingestion rate (mg/day)</td>
        <td width="34%">100 - resident adult<br>
        200 - resident child<br>
        50 - facility worker</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td width="33%">IRair</td>
        <td width="33%">Daily inhalation rate (m&#179;/day)</td>
        <td width="34%">20 - resident adult<br>
        15 - resident child<br>
        20 - facility worker<br>
        </td>
    </tr>
</table>
<p>NOTE: Equation variables, whether site-specific or default
values, must be based on a reasonable maximum exposure (RME) for
an individual under both current and reasonably anticipated
future land use conditions. Specifically, use of central tendency
values for equation variables is not allowed.<br>
<br>
<br>
Compiled by: Kenneth Mitchell, Ph.D.<br>
<br>
Date: 4/10/96</p>
<p>1. Equations 1, 2, 6, and 7 in Risk Assessment Guidance for
Superfund, Volume I - Human Health Evaluation Manual (Part B,
Development of Risk-Based Preliminary Remediation Goals),
Interim, USEPA (EPA/540/R-92/003), December 1991.</p>
<p>2. EPD shall be consulted if alternative sources of exposure
factors are contemplated.</p>
<p>3. For a discussion of RME see Risk Assessment Guidance for
Superfund, Volume I, Human Health Evaluation Manual (Part A),
Interim Final, USEPA (EPA/540/1-89/002), December 1989, page 6-4.</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
