<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type"
content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>STATE PROPOSES NEW GROUNDWATER STRATEGY</title>
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body stylesrc="http://www.dnr.state.ga.us/EPD/index.htm">
<p align="left">&#160;</p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica"><u>FOR IMMEDIATE
RELEASE:</u></font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="center"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">STATE PROPOSES
NEW GROUNDWATER STRATEGY</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">December 20, 1996
- Atlanta, Georgia. The Environmental Protection Division (EPD)
of the Georgia Department of Natural Resources has issued a plan
titled A Revised Interim Strategy for Managing Salt-Water
Intrusion in the Upper Floridan Aquifer of Coastal Georgia. This
new plan was prepared in response to more than 400 written and
oral comments received by EPD in response to a draft strategy
released in February 1996.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">The 24 coastal
counties of Georgia derive most of their drinking and industrial
process water supply from ground water. Most of this water comes
from the Upper Floridan Aquifer. Heavy dependence on this single,
prolific aquifer in Georgia, Florida, and South Carolina has
resulted in major drops in water pressure within the aquifer in
the Savannah, Brunswick, and the St. Marys-Fernandina Beach
areas. These drops in pressure have altered the flow of ground
water, which, in turn, has allowed sea water to enter the aquifer
in South Carolina (and possibly from offshore of Tybee Island)
and for deep brines to move upwards into the aquifer at Brunswick
and St. Marys-Fernandina Beach.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Computer modeling
of the aquifer shows that, at current rates of pumping, sea water
entering the aquifer in South Carolina, will reach Savannah in
about 100 to 300 years (depending on point of entry). Because of
these long predictions of time, the Revised Interim Strategy
proposes to allow more short term usage of the aquifer than the
February 1996 strategy would have allowed.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">The strategy
consists of the following components:</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
<blockquote>
    <blockquote>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Water-Supply
        Planning: Coastal Counties would prepare comprehensive
        water supply plans. Plans would be required for the
        central subarea and encouraged within the northern and
        southern subareas. Agricultural water-use data would be
        collected, annual agricultural water-use estimates
        calculated, and training provided on best management
        practices to conserve water.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Conservation:
        EPD would encourage conservation measures and the use of
        alternative water supplies. </font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Permitting:
        During the Interim Strategy, EPD would adjust existing
        municipal and industrial ground-water withdrawal permits
        to more closely reflect actual dry-year usage.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Sound
        Science: EPD, in cooperation with the U.S. Geological
        Survey, would conduct technical investigations of the
        salt-water intrusion into the Upper Floridan Aquifer.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">Fees: If
        approved by the General Assembly, EPD would collect fees
        from permitted users of the Upper Floridan Aquifer
        starting in 1998. These fees would be exclusively used to
        prepare comprehensive water supply plans, perform
        scientific studies, monitor aquifer conditions, and
        perform salt-water mitigation feasibility studies.</font></p>
        <p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
    </blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">EPD welcomes
public comment on the revised plan. For more information, contact
William Frechette at 404/656-3094.</font></p>
<p align="left"><font size="3" face="Helvetica">&#160;</font></p>
</body>
</html>
